---
/**
 * Fula Devi. Who she was, introduced through confirmed facts, remembered
 * events and authentic family photographs. The person, not the institution.
 * No moral is drawn after a memory — readers reach their own conclusions.
 *
 * All photographs are unaltered family originals: metadata sanitized, pixels
 * untouched. No generative restoration or facial reconstruction (see
 * docs/FULA_DEVI_IMAGE_ARCHIVE.md).
 */
import ContentPage from '../layouts/ContentPage.astro';
import Figure from '../components/Figure.astro';
import Quote from '../components/Quote.astro';
---

<ContentPage
  title="Fula Devi"
  description="Stories and photographs of Fula Devi, remembered for her everyday kindness, support for independence, and respect for people of different faiths."
>
  <p>
    Fula Devi (1958–2006) lived in Bihar, India. She was the mother of the
    institution's co-founder and the wife of its first secretary.
  </p>
  <p>
    Those who knew her remember the quiet kindness with which she treated
    people in everyday life.
  </p>

  <img
    class="portrait"
    src="/images/fula-devi/portrait/fula-devi-blue-sari-portrait.jpg"
    alt="Portrait of Fula Devi wearing a blue sari and looking toward the camera."
    width="735"
    height="1012"
    loading="eager"
    decoding="async"
  />

  <h2>She Preserved Dignity</h2>
  <p>
    During a blanket distribution organised by the institution in 2025, a
    former daily labourer who had worked for the family shared a memory from
    many years earlier.
  </p>
  <p>
    He recalled that when he came to the house at the end of each working day,
    Fula Devi fed him properly and offered more than once so that he would not
    feel shy about accepting enough.
  </p>

  <h2>She Helped Without Judgement</h2>
  <p>
    One of her friends later recalled that Fula Devi would quietly give her
    whatever money she could afford and always treat her with respect, even
    when others judged her.
  </p>

  <Figure
    src="/images/fula-devi/life/fula-devi-holding-painted-pot.jpg"
    alt="Fula Devi holding a decorated clay pot in a village setting."
    caption="Fula Devi holding a decorated clay pot."
    width={848}
    height={1272}
  />

  <h2>She Encouraged Independence</h2>
  <p>
    She encouraged her three daughters to become educated and financially
    independent.
  </p>
  <p>
    She supported them in applying for railway and police jobs at a time when
    such roles were often considered unsuitable for women.
  </p>

  <h2>She Respected Every Faith</h2>
  <p>
    Although she was a deeply religious Hindu, she encouraged her children to
    learn from any religion they wished to explore.
  </p>
  <p>
    She used to say that all gods are one and that religions teach the same
    lessons—like the same syllabus taught by different education boards.
  </p>
  <p>One family memory is of her sending her son to a mosque.</p>

  <Figure
    src="/images/fula-devi/pilgrimage/fula-devi-kanwar-yatra-with-husband.jpg"
    alt="Fula Devi and her husband participating in the Kanwar Yatra pilgrimage."
    caption="Fula Devi and her husband during the Kanwar Yatra."
    width={1200}
    height={1600}
  />

  <h2>Photographs</h2>
  <div class="gallery">
    <Figure
      src="/images/fula-devi/pilgrimage/fula-devi-kanwar-yatra-group-01.jpg"
      alt="Fula Devi standing with three other women during the Kanwar Yatra pilgrimage."
      caption="Fula Devi during the Kanwar Yatra."
      width={1600}
      height={1200}
    />
    {/*
      A second, visually distinct Kanwar Yatra photograph goes here.

      Only one qualifying photograph was supplied beyond the one used above.
      The remaining archived photograph (seated, yellow shawl) is a different
      occasion and is excluded from the public page by instruction, so the
      second slot is left unfilled rather than padded with a near-duplicate
      or an unrelated image. The grid already handles two items.
    */}
  </div>

  <h2>A Teaching Remembered</h2>
  <p>Her family remembers her saying, translated here into English:</p>
  <Quote attribution="An English translation of words remembered by her family.">
    Don't chant. Don't perform.<br />
    Search for the Owner in your body.<br />
    Serve the living.<br />
    Feed others. Give water to a cow.<br />
    That's worship. That's truth.
  </Quote>
</ContentPage>

<style>
  /* Page-local only — no global CSS, no new components. */

  /* The portrait sits below the title and stays subordinate to it.
     min() keeps the cap from overriding the global max-width:100%, which this
     more specific selector would otherwise beat — without it the portrait
     overflows its container on viewports narrower than about 470px. */
  .portrait {
    max-width: min(440px, 100%);
    margin-inline: auto;
  }

  /* Two columns on wider screens, one on mobile. No JS, no fixed-height
     crop: each photograph keeps its natural aspect ratio. */
  .gallery {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-6);
  }

  @media (min-width: 34rem) {
    .gallery {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
      align-items: start;
    }
  }

  /* Figures inside the grid are already spaced by the grid gap. */
  .gallery :global(figure) {
    margin: 0;
  }
</style>
